<br>
If you ran a VASIMR at an Isp of 200,000-400,000s you are going to take forever to accelrate to any resonible speed. For a 10MWe VASMIR, an Isp of 200,000s would yeild a thrust of about ~.2N, about twice the power of the ion thruster on DS1. I am not sure how the concept scales, so I don't want to try to extrapolate the figure up to a 200MWe+ system. Franklin Chang-Diaz HOPES to get the system up to 30,000s for high end(low thrust) operation, so 200,000s+ is a major leap from anything they expect in the near future. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nukepulse>NukePulse</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/23/02 5:37:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=197.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: vasimir</span><hr size=1> John<br>
<br>
I couldn’t agree more John. I do believe that at some point in the future a plasma drive MIGHT prove to be useful for fast lightweight scientific missions. I however do not believe that any other propulsion system other than ORION has a chance of becoming a prime mover for the industrialization of the solar system.<br>
<br>
For lightweight manned scientific missions, probes and non-industrial purposes other systems have value but only ORION offers the distinct possibility that an interplanetary industrial revolution can be initiated.<br>
<br>
Fusion powered super ORIONs could move colossal Industrial facilities into position close to sources of raw materials and then big fission powered ORION tugs could deliver finished products or refined materials to any destination in the Solar system cheaply. The best thing about ORION is that it scales up so nicely. <br>
<br>
Quote______________________________<br>
<br>
“Orion does it better (faster, more robust). Orion is all known technology -unlike VASIMR with superconductors in close proximity with contained plasmas and numerous other things.”<br>
<br>
That quote really says it all. Large ORIONs will need powerful subsidiary course correction thrusters so nuclear powered reaction control systems will be needed. Therefore we should focus some attention on small high thrust to weight ratio solid core nuclear engines for that purpose. I would rather see our time effort and money spent on ORION because it offers massive load carrying capacity, high performance and has few technical risks. <br>
<br>
The VASIMR requires several spectacular breakthroughs to become a reality. It needs a lightweight vapor core reactor that we don’t have the technology to build at the moment and also methods of insulating super-conducting coils against the radiant heat generated by the engine itself. I would just bet that developing a vapor core reactor powered VASIMR would take 20 years and cost as much as much as a few complete 4000 ton Orions that we could actually build and launch in a few years from today.<br>
<br>
For now let’s keep the effort and money on ORION and confine the fanciful high technical risk propulsion systems to the lab. ORION is really more bang for the buck.<br>
<br>
NukePulse<br>
