&quot;The artillery barrel is really not a good analogy as the shapes are entirely different and that does play into the strength of the structure.&quot;<br>
<br>
Note: I was wrong about the pressure that an M256 gun takes while firing its not 70,000 psi its approximately 110,000 psi. Also the duration of the pressure inside a high pressure gun is greater than  what a pusher plate would be required to endure on a shot for shot basis. On the down side it is also true that while a closed chamber suffers more erosion than a plate it is far less susceptible to elongation and distortion under pressure than a plate especially a large one. <br>
<br>
Of course the working end of a pusher plate is not a simple slab of metal that can withstand a certain amount of pressure and heat. A pusher plate consists of a metal disk backed by structural components to control resonance and distortion caused by shock and heat. Today a pusher plate would not be constructed from a homogeneous slab of steel like the original designers envisioned. Today we have metallic laminates that are far more resistant to any sort of stress than a simple slabs of steel.(1)<br>
<br>
Plate erosion and material migration under pressure seem to have been the biggest problems with pusher plates when the project was active. However it must be remembered that at the time they were being developed the most powerful computers available for modeling were not nearly as powerful as 386 PC with a 387 math co-processor. Those problems were never completely worked out so no completely satisfactory design was ever generated. <br>
 <br>
I am shocked that no one has mentioned the obvious fact that one of the very nice things about Orion is that  pulse unit yield, detonation distance, and pulse rate can be tailored to the actual performance parameters of the pusher plates and momentum conditioners that we can make right now.<br>
<br>
The challenges of designing workable pusher plates and momentum conditioners are not nearly as daunting or expensive as those that the plasma thruster and  GCNR devotes face. It is an absolute fact that we know more about how to build shock resistant structures than we do about how to contain plasmas or swirling maelstroms of vaporized uranium.(2)<br>
<br>
NukePulse<br>
<br>
<br>
(1) Today a 5-inch slab of laminated armor can provide the same level of protection that 1/2 meter+ of 1960’s style high strength homogenous steel armor. To the nitpickers yes resisting penetration by solid tungsten or depleted uranium slugs and high explosive shaped charges is not the same problem as a plasma wave hitting a pusher plate. The truth is that resisting penetration by those items is a far more challenging problem because of the intense pressures and heat involved.[millions of PSI])<br>
<br>
(2) “Because of the extreme operating conditions in a gas core engine, design issues in fluid mechanics, materials, thermal and radiation transport are at the state of the art or beyond. The gas core rocket development is a grand challenge commensurate with the capabilities of a national laboratory.”<br>
