<br>
“I am sorry, but barring MAJOR change, we'll never be able to launch an old-style Orion off the Earth, and I could see a real battle over a second or third stage system as well.&quot;<br>
<br>
I am not sure a ground launched Orion could have ever worked for several reasons that are directly related to the pulse rate required for it to be successful. In my view we have to get ORION into Space before turning the engine on.<br>
<br>
Reason 1) The pulse rate that a ground launched ORION would need to maintain an adequate rate of acceleration is far too high to be practical. With nuclear explosives detonating every second behind the ship the probability that one pulse will strike the plate off center is almost a certainty. If that happens the ship would begin to yaw and pitch and the subsequent pulses would send the beast spinning out of control. A 4000-ton ORION has a lot of inertia hence the reaction control system required to stabilize it would have to be huge. I seriously doubt that any reaction control system could keep the ship pointed in the right direction at a one pulse per second detonation rate. The pulse rate for Orion would have to be slowed down and that alone eliminates the possibility of a ground launch. <br>
<br>
Reason 2) This might shock and amaze some people but jams and misfires are a common occurrence in gun systems that are fed by autoloaders. Imagine what would happen during a ground launch if a charge got stuck in the feed mechanism or in the central deliver tube. Sadly, the faster you cycle an autoloader the more likely a stoppage is. Obviously for ORION a stoppage during its ascent to orbit phase is an instant ticket to the scrap heap. It would make the Challenger disaster look like a square dance. <br>
<br>
Orion is practical only in space where it can maintain a SLOW pulse rate and execute a vehicle stabilizing maneuver between each shot.<br>
<br>
Political Realities.  <br>
<br>
