 Orion has not nearly the amount of complete unknowns as the alternatives (even ICAN). Any improvements that make these merely more <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">feasible</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> make Orion more <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">certain</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; To the best of my knowledge, the only testing ever<br>
performed on materials survival in close proximity was<br>
carbon coated iron spheres. I suspect making a pusher<br>
plate survive is not as simple as we would like.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Tell it to George Dyson, Ted Taylor, (who's the other one mentioned in the book who's still working with the relevant software to this day?), E. Pederson, and the group working on GABRIEL/EPPP.<br>
As I said, if we don't know the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>best</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> ways around a question, we know several which could work. More than can be said for containing/controling plasmas and the &quot;Maelstroms of vaporised U&quot;.<br>
<br>
nebobgrenville<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>... compaired to many more advanced proposals, we<br>
can start now, there is no waiting for a new breakthrough<br>
to give the design a chance to work like ICAN or other<br>
designs require.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Basically my point, and don't forget the immediate potential for radically improved performance compared to anything else as close to flying off the drawing boards.<br>
<br>
